For international guests, you will need to present your passport upon checking in. They will make a photo copy of it.

They cleaned up the room every day for us. Be aware that you need to turn a switch on for the hot water. You must use your room key or the paper tag on the complimentary water and place it in the slot next to the light switches to turn everything on in the room.

The continental breakfast is from 7am - 10am. Breakfast is the same thing every morning. You can order a breakfast to go in the morning (it's just a sandwich and bottled water).

You may leave your room key at the front desk for the day if you would like. You may have to have the room key reprogrammed throughout your stay if you're there for a while.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"zillusia100","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QcqjfyADTZteN6UQjkfmI_GEkLkHcE0ELlx5mF7J8mlJ0xtKNb2Z0W14ZGUWvDdJggyxw=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"My 1st my impression of this hotel was good. How can this hotel allow overbooking of rooms and expect affected guest to compromise either to a lower quality hotel or to expect us to just combine our rooms? If the basic honoring of guest's booking can so easily be comprised, how can we ever trust this hotel again? To make things worse, we even went down personally to the hotel a few days before our check in date to ensure the hotel has our booking correctly received due to the prior similar incident happened in December 2018 when the hotel also says no room for us after we booked the rooms. Rooms were good, clean and well equipped. Breakfast was great, with omelettes cooked to order as well as the usual buffet fare. We travelled rounf Myanmar and returned to this hotel 2 weeks later to the same standard of service. title: Hotel Accord

descriptions: Simple rooms & suites in a casual hotel offering an airy restaurant & free breakfast.
user_reviews:
[{"Name":"Myo Thet Kyu","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjVqTMMPEWmJ_ABi8T-HDgXv57cXEFzvKmnHX-TvAVRICPeniuc=s120-c-rp-mo-br100","Rating":2,"Description":"just checked-in. although location is good, the room is dirty. But the bedsheets he brought still gots some stains on it. After  he saw the stains on the new bedsheet he brought, he asked me if I still want the new sheet. he continued saying that all the bedsheets will be like this although they got it from the new laundry bag. I friendly asked if they used the outsourced service for laundry, he answered yes. I friendly told him may be the laundry service place is not working properly.. still the housekeeper resists that the laundry service they used is used by most of the famous hotels in town. I am not expecting the best top notch services but after tiring long trip, I want the place I paid for still offer the bare minimum services like clean bed sheets, a working phone line, and the clean tables and desks.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Anthony Policano","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjWpjNo3VkwJLEQ-xqjh9_tk0PdvBE7vL9LDPnr7RNtrXramme0O=s120-c-rp-mo-ba4-br100","Rating":4,"Description":"Great hotel, great staff, great breakfast buffet (nice fruit plate for vegans), great central location next to a bustling local market, and always-on power with backup generator.

I stayed there twice, and my only complaint is that the first time my room was very small: for two people, we felt really cramped and couldn‚Äôt even walk past each other without someone jumping onto the bed to move out of the way (room 505), and one side of the bed didn‚Äôt have a table, and plugs behind the bed were difficult to access. The second time, the room (206) was at least a meter wider, had two bedside tables, and easy to reach plugs, which made all the difference! Another tiny complaint is that they offer water bottles but no easy-access to a more eco-friendly water refill station, but I asked the staff at the kitchen to help me and that always obliged (albeit with discomfort on their faces). Let‚Äôs do our part to use less single-use plastics!!

Other than that, I loved it.

TIP: there are a number of money changers nearby, but I only found one to sell my leftover MMK to for USD on departure, called WK at the bigger junction SW of the hotel.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Jordi Clement","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjV1SqkxobNOsWyLwPMFxQ_2731hIMK-DSX3qSmusyJBx1Xj1peTUQ=s120-c-rp-mo-ba3-br100","Rating":3,"Description":"So far so good. From my opinion too much money for the value but it was acceptable for Myanmar standards.
The breakfast was very nice and the staff kind and helpful. The room could be in better conditions and maintenance but as well, ok.. The location is nice.
The annoying thing was the elevator/ascensor: there's only one for the whole hotel so get ready to wait long periods of time to use it, all the staff is using it continuously through all day, up and down and down to up.. It's always busy with workers. The costumers will need to wait.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Trip.com Member","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeCck1CfANpZm9bBk3PHtP97Kh9k25HZfvq9yAWlN3BaIyjSHUPEfWkhAJmuYiJsH-_6g=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"Location in the city center Near hotel has local market Nice and good staff Hotel convince","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Exploration773782","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QcHdm0oAuHtzPwzcwUtTqUfPbZXmYnyyN78cO7_Z2aHVLpBkIuu0olTbSpOuQZcPV9sYQ=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"I stayed there 19 nighs. There are some good points (mostly) and a few bad ones. Fistly the staff is very friendly and supportive. There can be no complaints about them. Secondly the management acted very responsible, when I was in a health danger situation. I am very thankful to them for that. The bad points: One Aircon was not working and I was told beyond repair. I waited for a word of excuse (or even compensation) by the General Manger Mr. Smith Tin Win Aye, but that never happened. Finally i asked 2 time for an appointment, only to hear that "he is not free" "he is busy". Is that a proper way to behave by a GM ? I dont thinks so. Finally it must be mentioned that I could hear every word from the guests below my room. The hotel is run excellently with the utmost professionalism, while at the same time being so friendly and caring to its guests. The rooms are well furnished, clean, and modern. The hotels restaurant provides delicious meals too! Overall this place has been my home away from home- I highly recommend it!","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Jim L","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0Qdx0CtChWdL4amzhVtedU6JgNzs3A9KzPS8K998c7-u-mDeTb-7WQwuTD-PPX6BcVA5wg=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"I stayed at this hotel for two weeks. Hotel is about 20 minutes walk from Shwedagon and you can easily get taxis. One tip use the grab app to book taxis. Works so well and you know the price when you book. Taxis are safe and very cheap. The hotel has been upgraded with the same excellent service as before. The rooms are clean and maintained well. They even have an ATM in the lobby. There is a 24hour CityMart (local supermarket) nearby. Since the hotel is on the main road, you can easily get Grab (like Uber car sharing service) and go around the city.

Do read my previous review below:

*****************************
Old review from 2017 below:

We stayed in the hotel for 3 nights in the Superior twin room and 2 nights in the Junior Suite B with Bathtub. As most of the reviews have already mentioned,  choose the rooms towards the back of the hotel (away from the road) and preferably to the right (facing east), these rooms have a better view and also you will get a glimpse of the rising sun. The hotel's buffet breakfast is great and each day they have a special local cuisine. This, in my opinion, would be a very safe way to try out the local dishes. The staff can speak English and are very friendly. The rooms are clean and we'll  maintained. The only problem is  that the doors do not appear to be sound proof and could be a problem if there are a lot of guests moving in-and-out of their rooms. TIP: There is a City Mart outlet straight down the road, about 15mins walk. There is a hospital nearby. There are some great food places in about 15mins walk.  (Note: photos are from the Junior Suite B room #403)","Images":["www.google.com/local/imagery/report/?cb_client=maps_sv.tactile&image_key=!1e10!2sAF1QipNTRys335Gz8GYnI6YYBqGeugAo2Gk_wDNJK7Uv&fid=0x0:0x2c8d2472717556e6"],"When":"2018-1-7"},{"Name":"Sandy‚Äôs Shine","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjXd9XwYaXMx0VXxehGbmy_BXGG7o4D1R7qOLglJAXom2nLJ9IM=s120-c-rp-mo-br100","Rating":5,"Description":"Best technology in the leather industry","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Ian Borja","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjUNLX_Fs9Bq4tJkkoiCk_V6a2wYuYVowqo_cuP2tYcQNCXRug1DBw=s120-c-rp-mo-ba6-br100","Rating":5,"Description":"Small hotel of about 20 rooms. They do have good bed sheets, nice cozy room, very clean toilet and bathroom, and their towels are nice too.

They also have a simple buffet breakfast but would surely be filling. They have the normal fried rice, noodles, veggies, fishball, mominga, congee, bread, coffee & tea, different spreads, cereal, juice and fruits.

All staff, including the owner James, are very friendly  and they will make sure you will have the best stay.

Downside is location is in a main highway, but the noise is bearable. It is located a bit far from downtown area. Cab fare though is very inexpensive in Myanmar especially if you use Grab. If you let the front desk of the hotel book your Grab ride, you will even get a.discount.

title: Great Glory Hotel
address: V57Q+646 Great Glory Hotel, Ngar Man Aung Paya St, Yangon
descriptions: Unassuming hotel offering a bar, plus an open-air rooftop restaurant with creek views.
user_reviews: [{"Name":"S L","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeFH6dzZjd_ZFLhXHZKibEzXEy8hWzFB4Qa7PutLe3CnO2G7yVfjd4VSabiCQwQYo5W-g=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"Stayed here for 3 nights in August, very convenient location for Yangon airport.  I arrived after midnight and the staff were still very polite and helpful, typically Burmese style.   Unfortunately there was a problem with the air conditioning in my room but again they were courteous and helped me change my room, The room was basic but comfortable and clean.  Views from the airy roof top restaurant were wonderful.  As my flight out was at 1am the hotel had no problems with a late check out time of 9pm which was very kind of them.  WiFi was good too considering this is Yangon.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"ZRJT","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0Qcacbd8SUzOZ5BFqcuH0dUXFfPFzIfRWlhBQfTV3kcVPU69oUP_k10j49o8svvEcoldiA=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"Outstanding staff and attention to detail. We love this place and stayed here twice during our time in Yangon. The staff are exceptional and it was very clean. The hotel has seen better days but everything in both of the rooms we stayed in was fully functional - excellent a/c, very reliable internet (better than many other more expensive places in Yangon). The rooms we chose were quiet and, as I was working whilst traveling, that was essential. The manager and his wife went out of their way to make sure we had the best of stays. I am looking forward to our future visits and cannot recommend it highly enough. Free breakfast on the rooftop until 10 am. The room is clean and spacious, with very good AC. Sometimes there is no hot water, but it doesn't matter since it's always +35 in Yangon. They have three bunnies in the lobby :D The hotel is not in the city, but that's how you get to see the local life. Everything around is cheap, people are nice, no one tried to rip us off except the three wheelers... To get to the city: after getting on the main road, turn left and walk straight for about 3 kilometers until you see a bridge, don't pass it, walk under it, and you can take the famous circular train to the city center for 20 US cents. Also, taxi from the airport to the hotel should only cost 5000 kyats, which is about $4. title: Hotel Shwe Eain Taw

user_reviews:
[{"Name":"Theo","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjX1q9-gRFTa-cXzjc58mcRbRj__l9RydXLgOSW0ZmxRcQ0xXuRm=s120-c-rp-mo-ba5-br100","Rating":4,"Description":"This is my new favorite hotel. The prices here at the time I got here was a bargain!

You get to have free breakfast and a very large room for under $15.

Not too bad...

The only downside is the location. It is terribly far from anywhere I deem fun and exciting. It is 50 minutes away walking distance to the park. 45 minutes away from a decent gym. The market is also 20 minutes of walking.

If you are a solo traveller who loves to walk and loves affordable stays that punches above it's weight. Stay here!","Images":["www.google.com/local/imagery/report/?cb_client=maps_sv.tactile&image_key=!1e10!2sAF1QipP0YIweIXQ2WTpaUERafUUsjhqZ0YKEz5uIycz0&fid=0x0:0x1b5bc3fb87e20b49"],"When":"2024-1-14"},{"Name":"Steve R","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeFH6dzZjd_ZFLhXHZKibEzXEy8hWzFB4Qa7PutLe3CnO2G7yVfjd4VSabiCQwQYo5W-g=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"I booked the hotel for 3 of us in a family room for 3 nights. We were running the Yangon marathon (superb) and it is 2k from the start we walked home its that close.  ||||The hotel dosnt look great with ageing decor and a tired looking exterior. Thats where the negatives stop. ||||Firstly lets put this in perspctive,our room cost 63 usd (20 bucks each) including a very nice breakfast. ||||On arrival we were greeted with an orange juice and taken to our room by 3 porters lugging our bags up 4 stories to our room. We had a fantastic view (see picture), flat screen tv with sports and movies in english, newly installed air con, en suite with electric shower (reliably warm) and comfortable beds with clean sheets and towels. What else do you want. ||||The staff are so helpful bringing up water, beers, food and anything else we needed no matter what time of the day. The breakfast is great and they even remember if you like ketchip or chilli sauce and your choice of fruit the next day. The eggs are perfect!||||On the last night I sat and watched football with the local guys on a 40" TV and we had a great laugh whilst I ate my excellent 3 dollar special fried rice packed with chicken, pork, prawns...that I had no chance of finishing due to the volume.||||All in all a fantastic place which is 15 mins from airport and anything else in the city.  With taxis costing about 3 dollars to just about anywhere.  ||||This is not the ritz but is clean, authentic with great people. I would stay here again and again.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Canndy H","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeYuXGoFc9HnT35lAJ46cKDIsHY7nNIKUKz_f8yINNlqyrU48jCx-4ctPzihRKgde030w=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"The location is away from the city but transportation is not the problem as Yangon city is a TAXI city. title: Asian Smile Hotel
address: No. 324, Thanthumar Road, Thuwanna, Yangon 11072
user_reviews:
[{"Name":"Brandon Rudd","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocL3BEm67ErtBvBTnTEY_JdnDPNZmcEPQkFQ8FQpZRsN2KeORA=s120-c-rp-mo-br100","Rating":5,"Description":"An amazing place to stay if you really want to get lost in Myanmar! The staff are super kind and helpful, alongside being quite amusing at times.

They may not speak much English but they more than make up for it with service, not to mention they are very generous. A person here let me borrow some flip flops for the time I went to pagoda and helped me dress in their traditional outfit. Thanks to them I have a great experience in the country.

The location is pretty convenient too if you use the grab app, you can book a taxi and take a ride to downtown in about 10 minutes.

The room also has all the basic necessities and even come with free body wash and shampoo incase you run out as well as toothbrush.

The power may go out a few times but thats not their fault, its the countries power grid with rolling blackouts and they try to keep the power going with a generator I believe. The hot water in the shower is a little short but with how hot the country is it didn't bother me.

Hopefully they see this so thank you Asian Smile Hotel!!!","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Myo Myint oo","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjXOmactE_SsuEBl2unndIH-zfOLgexF7ZWcsQAWzZo2mqLLULTKcA=s120-c-rp-mo-ba7-br100","Rating":3,"Description":"Wide and clean room. title: Wishton Hotel
address: No.365, Thitsar Road and Shwe Thitsar Street (Corner),No.13 Ward, Yangon
descriptions: Relaxed hotel featuring straightforward quarters with balconies, plus a gym, a cafe/bar & breakfast.
complete_address: {"borough":"","street":"No.365, Thitsar Road and Shwe Thitsar Street (Corner),No.13 Ward","city":"Yangon","postal_code":"","state":"","country":"MM"}
user_reviews:
[{"Name":"Ako Linn","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjU81170LiobW34fSs6lQEhLyYMbtcDoKGDvyr6wzh9z0OFovXdt3w=s120-c-rp-mo-br100","Rating":5,"Description":"I would be happy to write a review of Japanese hospitality in Myanmar!

Japanese hospitality, also known as "omotenashi," is known for its attention to detail, sincerity, and warmth. During my recent trip to Myanmar, I had the pleasure of experiencing this hospitality firsthand at a Japanese-owned hotel.

From the moment I arrived, I was greeted with a warm smile and a refreshing welcome drink. The staff went above and beyond to make sure that my stay was comfortable and enjoyable. They were always available to answer any questions I had and to provide recommendations for things to see and do in the area.

One of the things that stood out to me was the attention to detail. The room was immaculate, with every amenity I could possibly need, from a comfortable bed to a well-stocked minibar. The hotel also offered a range of complimentary services, including a daily breakfast.

But what really made my stay special was the warmth and sincerity of the staff. They truly seemed to care about my well-being and went out of their way to make me feel at home. Whether it was a friendly conversation in the lobby or a kind gesture like a the staff always made me feel welcome and valued.

Overall, I would highly recommend this Japanese-owned hotel to anyone visiting Myanmar. The combination of Japanese hospitality and Myanmar's natural beauty and culture made for an unforgettable experience. Thank you to the staff for making my stay so memorable!","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Jamie O","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0Qdx0CtChWdL4amzhVtedU6JgNzs3A9KzPS8K998c7-u-mDeTb-7WQwuTD-PPX6BcVA5wg=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"I stayed for one month at Wishton while working at Myanmar Plaza. The size was great. A lot of space to hang clothes as well as shelves, which meant I didn't have to live out of my suitcase.||||The bathroom was modern and efficient. The strong water-pressure and instant hot water made the shower a wonderful experience. The bath was nice and spacious as well.||||The wifi was good, being better at night for some reason. Another point for this hotel is easy to access to the city center while you are not in the middle of roads where traffic is terrible most of the time. Really love this place.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Egil √òstlid","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjUV5D39QmW7t1TMpjc3BQJtkZJ7Xb4C1jRgi_eOalOOsBBCu7tm=s120-c-rp-mo-ba3-br100","Rating":4,"Description":"Good place to stay for a few days in Yangon, Myanmar","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"AlSandiego73","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QfjHmZg8gr7jpDgKhrh5KsR_Mq7L6pkVedvpKQz-f3LMiOd3OjI90CK4uLtF3wE59zZgA=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"I spent a total of six nights at the Royal Ruby split into two stays, so I feel pretty qualified to review this property. The most important thing to know going in is that this is a fairly small hotel. The lobby is quite compact, and even though there is a couch there usually are 2-4 people hanging out (I could never tell if they were all hotel employees or just friends). ||||For both stays I was given room #8004, right around the corner from the front desk. It might be the largest room in the hotel - there was a big, flat-screen TV, some comfortable chairs, a twin bed, and a double bed. The air conditioning was pretty strong but could be adjusted with the remote. For the first 3-4 nights there were a couple of mosquitoes that had gotten into my room somehow which made sleeping a bit difficult (I tend to attract them) in spite of the A/C being on.||||The bathroom is small but totally functional. I appreciated the modern fixtures, especially the square-shaped sink with a fairly deep basin. No problems with hot water or water pressure.||||Breakfast is served on the roof where there is an indoor eating area as well as outdoor tables. The manager, U Shwe (Mr. Gold), has done a nice job turning the outdoor space into something of a sanctuary by stringing vines and plants over the balcony so that you don't really see the busy and dusty street below. It's very green and pretty comfortable, but it's the only place to \"hang out\" and is not free from mosquitoes since it's outside.||||The choices at breakfast are quite diverse and do rotate, so if you stay for a few days you'll see different dishes. Mostly Myanmar-style food with rice, noodles (usually oily), vegetables, soup, a couple of meat dishes, etc. though there is fruit and a couple of different bread products with butter and jam. U Shwe is always at breakfast and does a great job making guests feel at home, even to the point of plating food for them and bringing it to the table. His English is excellent and he's very helpful, so if you have any questions and/or need assistance of any kind be sure to seek him out.||||The location of this hotel is a half-block off of a busy street (Yadanar Road) that doesn't have a sidewalk and isn't really walkable. There is a Chinese/Thai-style restaurant just half a block up that is a good option if you don't want to eat at the Royal Ruby. It's on the same side of the street and serves decent food. ||||There is free wi-fi at the Royal Ruby, but as is often the case in Myanmar the connection seems to go in and out randomly. I was unable to connect with my iPhone but had no problem with my laptop, and in the mornings (before 9am) and evenings (after 7pm) the connection on my laptop was pretty good.||||The only reason I stayed at this hotel was because it is close to the offices of the organization that hosted me during my stay. It's not one that I normally would choose for myself, but it was perfectly adequate for most of my needs. Since there is no fitness center I took a taxi to Real Fitness on Pale Road just west of Kabar Aye Pagoda Road in Bahan. They charge US$20 for a session during weekdays and US$30 on weekends...pretty steep, but I really needed a workout.||||If I go back to Yangon and need to be in this part of town, I most likely would choose to stay at the Sedona Hotel. If you need something a bit on the cheaper side, though, the Royal Ruby should work for your needs. My room was US$60/night (payable in cash, even though there's a MasterCard sign at the reception desk) which apparently is standard for that class of hotel in Yangon. The best thing about the Royal Ruby is U Shwe - I wouldn't even have bothered reviewing this property if he hadn't been such a great resource.||||P.S. I left a piece of luggage at the hotel while I traveled to Inle Lake and Bagan and stopped by to pick it up five days later. No problem with that.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Mel G","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0Qf66pF81jsVXBxevYxxL5FsdlDsKAngAUpJVE-hAwai1rl8J0QnYqktKV3UGdpbmNlc_A=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"The royal Ruby is anew hotel just a year old, it has 39 rooms, the receptionist speaks workable English and the manager check every room for cleanliness everyday twice he insists and as I seem home running around checking things and training his new staff one and half hours every day it's a bit like being in hotel training school as everyone tries to help in this B and B trying to go up market. I had difficulty trying to organise flights on the Internet to Mruak U and after the receptionist used the phone a friend option a taxi driver with good English turned up and drove me to the airline office and a money changing shop to get the best rate which it was it turned out. The rooms are spotless with that Asian guesthouse eyesore to most westeners the wet bathroom. Yep when you use the shower if you can stop splashing the toilet if you stand up western shower not squat Asian wash style. I was the only non Asian in the place. They gave me a said count for travelling alone, I didn't,t ask for it. There is the mini bar and flat screen and individual air on unit that was all working as we'll as power adapter and multipoint charging station. Free wifi and about dial in speed which I think is not their limitation. Breakfast is certainly set up for Asian with the congee soup, noodles and there is always the eggs and toast to fall back on. The Asian sweetened bread is not my cup of tea so perhaps I should have stuck to the local fare but wanted to try the western option. There is a very good oriental restaurant about fifty yards away with dim sum on Sunday and some of the best and fastest food service for an experienced foodie. No pool or gym only it's own dining room but clean safe secure and cooperative. A cab ride to town is cheap the driver they organised with good English took me for the days travel for not much more than my original rip off airport connection. I suspect the owner is still a general so you can't get away from that. There was also no construction when I was there. My room is huge (and ceiling high), the television is so far away (8-10m) from my bed I have problem seeing the details. In contrast my hotel room in the city centre was so small that the TV is mounted like 80cm from the bed and they have to put it near the ceiling to increase the distance. The rooms are very well furnished (best value for money IMHO) and bigger than the family room that I had booked at the nearby Crystal Palace Hotel. It is a modern hotel with card entry. If you stay at the hotel you get a 20% discount at the Spa and the ONLY treatment I would recommend is the traditional massage at 10,000 kyat before discount. The Monalisa Restaurant (Level 1) is actually excellent and reasonably priced that I ended having dinner there every night. The breakfast is not excellent but quite good. There is actually an omelette counter so you can have you eggs done in any way but I did not see any eggs swimming in grease.||While the Wifi is not great, the signal is relatively strong and it is actually better than most hotels in Myanmar. Internet speed is not fast in the whole country and may break off.||Having stayed at various locations in Yangon, I can say this hotel is very centrally located. You can walk to visit Chauk Htat Gyi and Nga Htat Gyi Pagodas and be back within 2 hours without rushing. Shwedagon is also within walking distance.Downtown and Kandawgyi Lake are also not far away.  ||The best thing about this hotel is the hot water. You get very hot water very fast, better than some 5 star hotels.||Try not to venture to the basement as it is a "Love Tunnel" mostly for the local businessmen. The hotel staff is helpful, friendly and professional. Highly recommended, it is unbeatable at the price I paid. The only negative about this hotel is that there are no shops, shopping centres or amenities nearby. There is a diesel generator planted at the entrance of the hotel so any electrical outages are very short.","Images":null,"When":""}]

Hotel itself could do with some money being spent on it as the carpets are frayed but the room was very large with a great wooden floor. user_reviews:
[{"Name":"Wai Yan Min Khant","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocIs1pY9NKlkN9KPMB4P0N0kKcSTo-GEwdfNGYXheBvsCoh2Bf8=s120-c-rp-mo-br100","Rating":2,"Description":"I would like to offer some constructive feedback for service improvement based on our recent stay at your hotel on 16-17. We chose your hotel after carefully comparing reviews and services from other options, but unfortunately, the experience fell short of our expectations and what the reviews suggested.

Firstly, we called ahead at noon to inquire about early check-in but were told it wasn‚Äôt possible. We understand that early check-in is subject to availability, but this was disappointing. We checked in at 2 p.m. as directed.

During the check-in process, the reception team did not thoroughly verify our booking details. They requested full payment upfront despite our prior payment of half the charges via Kpay. We had to remind them to recheck the information, which was frustrating and could have easily been avoided with better attention to detail.

Secondly, our room was not ready upon arrival, even though we had informed the reception in advance of our arrival time. When escorted to the room, the staff knocked before entering, which raised concerns about whether they were unsure if the room was properly assigned to us. Additionally, the key card provided didn‚Äôt work, leaving us waiting outside for an extended period. The staff eventually opened the room with a master key but left us with the malfunctioning card instead of replacing it with a functional one. This was not only inconvenient but also unprofessional.

The state of the room itself was also disappointing. The bed was not properly organized, and the decorative pillows and blanket shown in your promotional photos were haphazardly stored in the wardrobe rather than being arranged on the bed. This lack of attention to detail made us question whether the room had been properly cleaned after the last guest‚Äôs stay. The staff member assisting us also did not offer any information about the facilities, and their tone and demeanor were far from what one would expect from hospitality staff. We felt disrespected and unwelcome.

Lastly, communication between staff was noticeably poor. Upon leaving for dinner, we informed the reception about the faulty key card and handed it over for replacement. However, when we returned, the staff on duty seemed unaware of the situation and even questioned whether we had handed in the key at all. This clear lack of communication between shifts added to our dissatisfaction.

Overall,  the service we received was far from the standard we anticipated, and we hope these issues will be addressed for future guests.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Pearl Su","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocKmPkagE-Z23PA_7GpkkzZQ94VuUT3WYlPp5b7EJRlt0Efunw=s120-c-rp-mo-ba4-br100","Rating":4,"Description":"It is located inside of the alley. user_reviews: [{"Name":"Nick N","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeNj0UTN0yIrCGyJ0JhWwDODOg5QjAH0gdfB9Ji-oFl0zWFI-YVmhNAr-FGLycdpIjFmw=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"The desk staff was awesome!!  They were very helpful and spoke a good bit of English.  The upscale home turned hotel, looked tired and in need of repair.  But there was a lot of very nice woodwork all around and the hotel had \"character,\" for sure! ||||I personally enjoyed sitting out by a small balcony reading and watching the birds.  ||||They had a free breakfast in another next door restaurant which four breakfast options.  The breakfast was very good, and the waiters/waitresses were very friendly and helpful.  We had three of the four breakfast options and they were all good.||||Here was one of the meals:   Steamed Dimsum, fried noodles, chicken sausage,  sliced Honey Dew and Papaya with something on it that tastes like a perfume smells but is really good with coffee and Oolong tea.  Oh,  and some  kind of  a fish meat based hot sauce...also good.||||From the airport to the hotel we got a taxi from the taxi desk inside for 6,000 MMK but going back we found a taxi that only charged us 4,000 MMK.||||It was a nice place to stay on a budget!!  I would stay there again.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"ukairo_dash","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QcnOWm00_8Vg0_qD09-e04s-i2bb5F6bVsdwxSboR_yrT1yPvciwzMvgtJ8p5a3bvmZzg=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"Stayed at the Excel Palace for 4 nights of a month long stay in Yangon. So in an apples-to-apples comparison, it is close to 3 stars. . .  but falls short in several ways. You be the judge:||The room was large and wasnt lacking for furniture, but the drapes were badly torn and the bedding had a lot of visible stains.  ||The plush headboard was likewise filthy and the pillows were very well used.||Moving on to the bathroom, the shower had plenty of hot water but 75% flowed out if the downspout, leaving the shower with rather weak pressure. The shower head was mounted below chest level. I brought these issues up with the staff on day 1, but there was no change during our time there.||Finally, the free breakfast. It was next door in a busy restaurant. There is a choice of 4 set menus with no changes allowed (it is not a buffet). Most hotels (every one we have stayed at in Yangon) have a buffet. The restaurant wouldn't even give us water, only tea or coffee (which I doubt is from filtered water). The water at the hotel is turbid (a light brown color), and I imagine that is what you get with the tea/coffee.||We brought our own bottled every morning which was not a problem.||I would give details about the number of flies in the restaurant, but suffice it to say that if you dont like flies buzzing everywhere, you might want to avoid the place.||The location (walking distance to the lake) was ok. A longer walk to other restaurants (with the exception of a Thai restaurant just across the street which was excellent).||All in all, I'd like to give it 3 stars. The house is nice. They could quickly fix most issues. But it seems the management is not of a mind to follow through.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"John C","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0Qdx0CtChWdL4amzhVtedU6JgNzs3A9KzPS8K998c7-u-mDeTb-7WQwuTD-PPX6BcVA5wg=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"Hotels in Yangon, now that Myanmar is the \"flavour of the month\", are now very expensive with the xception of the Excel Palace. It is not downtown but close to Inya Lake and the Inya Lake Hotel which is where I wanted to be close to.||It is an old private home and has no lift but spiral staircases, so be warned.||My room was large with two twin beds. All shampoos, soap etc were all supplied, as was free water every day. There is a safe in the room. The WiFi worked well.||There is also a well stocked bar fridge and the beer price was cheaper than buying outside!||The reception staff could not be more helpful...nothing was too much trouble.||The included breakfast is not in the Hotel but just around the corner in a restaurant.||The service there was a mixture of very good, when the waitresses were working our table but a bit hit and miss when it was waiters!!||Taxis are everywhere and very cheap so it is easy to get to anywhere you want to go with no problems.||Would I stay there again...you bet I would...very happily.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Mike S","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0Qf66pF81jsVXBxevYxxL5FsdlDsKAngAUpJVE-hAwai1rl8J0QnYqktKV3UGdpbmNlc_A=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"We only arrived at 4pm and left at 5am the following morning but the service and assistance we received from the front desk was outstanding. We needed a bus booked the following morning and that was no problem ‚Äì they also had the taxi ready for us at 5am the following morning before we even got down to reception. The room itself was so big (but a refreshing change from some others), that it had two air conditioners. We were on the top floor ‚Äì if you have an irrational fear of pigeons, maybe request a room on a lower floor, as we had a few scratching around on the roof, not enough to wake us up though.||||We didn‚Äôt get to try breakfast before we left. There are a few decent looking restaurants right near the hotel although we didn‚Äôt get a chance to try them either. The Excel Palace is in walking distance to Inya Lake and only a short drive to Shwedagon. Unless you want to be in walking distance of Sule Paya and Bogyoke Markets, I‚Äôd recommend this place purely for the service.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"kayk44","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QdGDJ6WBs5CBoNVcQAwShh25kntoFa0rN3szxhkmmJHnXagNPuSfO1BRpzbnKc5wyCe_g=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"We stayed at Excel Palace Hotel for 22 days.  First and foremost, we mention our #1 staff.  Simon, the manager, and also the assistant manager who went out of their way to assist us.  From city directions, room comfort, even impromptu language lessons, they were there with a smile.  Our room was comfortable, clean and quiet.  The location of the hotel, just off New University Avenue, allowed for peaceful nights, no traffic noise at all.  There are good restaurants nearby and downtown is just a short taxi ride away.  We will certainly return to Excel Palace when returning to Yangon.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"neamman","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeiIm6t64oXJwlfKKV-SU2ENLb40SwZCvBWRts5o7WimonLggB5R8bs4qOdTbCTDXjyRQ=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"An old converted house which provided what I expected for the price paid. Staff very friendly and helpful, location reasonable for the price..facilities old and somewhat dated but no problems. title: Residence 26
address: 26 ·Äô·Äº·Ä±·Äî·ÄØ·Äú·Äô·Ä∫·Ä∏, Yangon
user_reviews:
[{"Name":"Megha Sardar","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocLdD8sE7hoJKWRABF7obJeM8QYKmEuA6AWXZnx4nZqOVudK3AEV=s120-c-rp-mo-ba2-br100","Rating":5,"Description":"I stayed here for 21 days during a business trip..Rooms are great.. I got a suite room with all amenities and service is great. People are very polite and well behaved. There's a gym at the top floor and wifi is available throughout.

Few cons:
food is only available in the restaurant during morning.
Cafe@26 in front of the hotel offers great food though.
Also, power cuts are frequent but they have proper backup and it comes back within 5 mins.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Eric R","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QcHdm0oAuHtzPwzcwUtTqUfPbZXmYnyyN78cO7_Z2aHVLpBkIuu0olTbSpOuQZcPV9sYQ=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"I wrote my first review a few months ago, and I have returned twice since, for stays of about a month each time.  By now, the feeling of a "home-away-from-home" has definitely cemented.  The staff knows who the guests are, and cheerfully greet them each time.   They bend over backwards to accommodate the guests, and the facility is getting better and better, including the whole-building generator which makes the now-frequent and increasingly long (4-6 hours) power interruptions more than bearable.  Maintenance of the serviced apartments is prompt and thorough, and the sales (Ma Choo Yee) and accounting staff could not be more helpful.  The biggest surprise, though, is the improvement in the Cafe@26, their on-site restaurant.  Although small (seating  about 40), it now has a Myanmar chef returning from Dubai, who specializes in Italian cuisine having trained with Italian chefs.  He has added daily specials which are consistently good, fresh seafood (you have not really "lived" until you've tried the Ngapali shrimp!), and outstanding pasta dishes.  With their soon to be awarded liquor license, one can only hope that a good selection of wine and beer will complement the excellent cuisine.  Add the well trained English-speaking serving staff, the result is that Cafe@26 has become a destination restaurant, especially for the Sanchaung and surrounding townships crowd, starting to rival the nearby SHARKY's.  As always, we can only hope that they will continue to keep constant the high standard that they have started with.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"JC D","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0Qdx0CtChWdL4amzhVtedU6JgNzs3A9KzPS8K998c7-u-mDeTb-7WQwuTD-PPX6BcVA5wg=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"Situated in the heart of Yangon, Residence@26 is a smart, newly completed and fully serviced apartment complex.  ||||The facilities, furnishings and fittings are of the highest standard throughout.  Each apartment is fully self-contained and includes king size bed(s), a kitchen and dining area and the larger apartments have en-suite bathrooms: Wi-Fi and air conditioning are standard. ||||Staff are extremely friendly and helpful throughout.  Apartments are cleaned daily, and a laundry service is available if required.  On the upper ground floor there is a laundry room for the more energetic resident.  On the top floor there is a well-equipped gymnasium which, with floor to ceiling windows, offers spectacular panoramic views over Yangon. The world famous Shwedagon Pagoda is within walking distance and readily seen.||||A further advantage of Residence@26 is that it has also has a restaurant which is available to guests and non-guests alike.   All dishes are made to order by the Italian chef and sous chef using fresh ingredients: all are highly recommended. ||||Having stayed in Residence@26 on three separate occasions I have yet to find fault with the place.  In essence I consider it to be home from home and have no hesitation in highly recommending it to others.  I am looking forward to my next visit.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"thazin n","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeqQESQs2CRf2VRyln1Raq0k2FSdB19mGKme5Xh6nHXcs2V7pTrOayJAdxC-qWdu9VyTA=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"I recommend to go this residenc,it is convenient for who will stay for long stay or short stay .Quiet ,Clean and feels like home.I like that the fridge is big enough .I will come back.I stay at one Bed Room suit that is bed room living room and  dinning &Kitchen area.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Eric R","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QcHdm0oAuHtzPwzcwUtTqUfPbZXmYnyyN78cO7_Z2aHVLpBkIuu0olTbSpOuQZcPV9sYQ=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"Newly built (they're still working on the penthouse, which may become a bar), this serviced apartments outstanding property is well managed, and offers high-end furnishings in very large, high ceiling suites.  The building comes with a whole-building generator, which is really handy in a city where power failures are all too often, and varying in length of time.  The A/C mini splits are high-end Japanese units, the newly-finished gym is well equipped and has a three-sided spectacular view of Yangon (it's on the top floor), the small Cafe@26 is a cozy place to have your daily breakfast (included), or an intimate lunch or dinner.  Their chefs are Italian-trained, so the pasta is truly excellent. As of this writing, they had not yet received the liquor license, which is expected by next year.  The monthly rental includes laundry up to 120 garments (each of which comes back wrapped in individual bags!), although there are self-laundry facilities on the G2 floor.  The staff speaks varying degrees of English, but is enthusiastic and very helpful.  In a nutshell, when you leave you want to take them home, as their level of dedication to the job is second to none.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Eric Rose","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjWYn3Yewlj8SGGPPRnBIRM-F5JzUIICxKoY9RFSZrqPlIwM4HScqA=s120-c-rp-mo-ba3-br100","Rating":5,"Description":"Having stayed here multiple times for weeks-on-end since it's opening three years ago, it has become my favorite "home-away-from-home."  The staff knows who the guests are, and cheerfully greet them each time.  They bend over backwards to accommodate the guests, and the facility is getting better and better, including the well equipped gym with it's panoramic 8th floor view of Yangon, and the whole-building generator which makes the now-frequent and long, at times (3-4 hours), power interruptions more than bearable.  Maintenance of the serviced apartments is prompt and thorough, and the staff could not be more helpful.  The biggest surprise, though, is the improvement in the Cafe@26, their on-site restaurant.  Although small (seating about 40), it now has an Italian chef who specializes in ... you guessed it ... outstanding pasta dishes üòâ.  He has added daily specials which are consistently good, fresh seafood (you have not really "lived" until you've tried the Ngapali shrimp!), and outstanding local dishes.  Recently, they added a basic selection of wine and beer which complement the excellent cuisine.  Add the well trained English-speaking serving staff, the result is that Cafe@26 has become a destination restaurant, especially for the Sanchaung and surrounding townships crowd, starting to rival the nearby SHARKY's.  As always, we can only hope that they will continue to keep constant the high standard that they have started with.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Ben S","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QfHhPp0vyvo1Wo3WY4NH1G5QOPAHGBMv_XiebXLZtHzVwVa3wkRhb3dykyKrUCZPlawDA=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"The building is an "up and coming" part of Yangon, I've added some photos of the exterior views so you can see what that means - walls with climbing plants and black mould, corrugated iron roofs with trees growing through them, etc. - but inside you could - almost - be in Singapore or Hong Kong, the apartments are new and modern. The colour scheme is a bit too cool black and white, but it doesn't matter because everything works very well. There is a nice and reasonably priced cafe on the 2nd floor and a gym on the 7th floor with views directly over Shwedagon Pagoda, which is great. There's also an outdoor rentable space on the 7th floor which I haven't used yet. The staff are very helpful and friendly and the location is conveniently - basically between the airport and downtown, about 20 minutes drive to downtown on a good day. Overall excellent, the only downside being the cost, which is as you would expect, expensive. Still, cheaper than a hotel if you are staying for a month or so, and a much better experience.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Annelien L","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QfjHmZg8gr7jpDgKhrh5KsR_Mq7L6pkVedvpKQz-f3LMiOd3OjI90CK4uLtF3wE59zZgA=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"This was the second time in 4 months I stayed here and they indicated that in the welcome letter by welcoming me back again. It's a small boutique hotel with great service and quality and excellent facilities in a lovely and central neighbourhood. I feel I am just lucky to have found it and will definitely spend any other trip in this lovely gem.","Images":null,"When":""}]

user_reviews:
[{"Name":"Trip.com Member","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeCck1CfANpZm9bBk3PHtP97Kh9k25HZfvq9yAWlN3BaIyjSHUPEfWkhAJmuYiJsH-_6g=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"A budget hotel with very friendly and helpful staff, offering a good breakfast with a buffet. Note that the rooms have a shared bathroom, which should be taken into account. The internet connection can occasionally be interrupted, so it‚Äôs better to have your own SIM card for work","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Matthew Ortiz","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjXRWq-BNP10zsikF7cEz4hQxZ-OBwASD31FTupiRHyjoAXQoc0=s120-c-rp-mo-ba4-br100","Rating":2,"Description":"At first it looks like a very good deal, a whole apartment with 2 bedrooms and 2 bathrooms for a low price.¬† When you see how dirty it is then the price makes sense.

But, you are given 2 doorlocks for the two bedroons, there is no doorlock to the main living room.¬† At firsr it seemed like just a strange inconvenience because they are "changing locks" but in hindsight I think this is just a socially acceptable excuse but in hindsight I believe it to be deception (based on their behavior of just entering the room when they feel like it.

The first time my wife was surprised and they were blessed by getting to see to much of her.¬† After that they kept coming back again and again under the guise of being extra helpful.

Their behavior was polite but I found it completely unacceptable.¬† At night I¬† dragged the couch in front of the door and put another chair on top of it and leaned against the door so that if someone tried to push the door opened then the chair should fall off and make a loud noise and alert me that someone was trying to enter the room at night.¬† At 11am exactly I heard the staff in the room.¬† They had come in to clean the room (without calling first) an hour before checkout time.

When I went out I saw how he had quietly and carefully wedge the door open already expecting that there was such a trap; showing that he had developed this skill over time and that he was aware that he was sneaking in instead of calling.

I was enraged!¬† I come from Texas where the law says that if someone did this at either my home OR A HOTEL that I would have the legal right to kill them.

I know that Myanmar law does not allow that and I respect Myanmar law; however they need to realize that they are authorized for foreign customers and they should try to give reasonable respect that when we are paying to sleep in a place that we have a right to privacy.

I cannot consider this hotel to be safe as you are not entitled to security of a safe space.

I have talked to Myanmar friends and this behavior is also not acceptable by their own culture.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Trip.com Member","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeCck1CfANpZm9bBk3PHtP97Kh9k25HZfvq9yAWlN3BaIyjSHUPEfWkhAJmuYiJsH-_6g=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"Smokers room and unable to sleep in room, called the reception they offered air freshener when I had booked a non-smoking room. Slept in hallway, got eaten by mosquitoes. Also on the 8th floor and no elevator. Not a restful room. Great location though.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Marijn Dr√∂ge-Rotteveel","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjXXx19PpyVZES6ZYWv0W8jmzX1gCnK71tSI4I4Wu7T68rQMYDTm3g=s120-c-rp-mo-br100","Rating":5,"Description":"Our number 1 hotel to go in Yangon.  Clean rooms, good staff, good location.  They were even waive our cancelation fees since we had an emergency.  Very good hotel. Will be coming back regularly.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Naung Mon Oo","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjXu0YiordMk92v9mfW81SkmwOkJ6vURbRnkQ3-6uy7fORonHhsF_A=s120-c-rp-mo-ba4-br100","Rating":1,"Description":"I don't want to, but I have to say this: this hotel has the worst service. The staff isn't helpful; they can't smile, and some even have a bad attitude. They don't seem to care about the customers at all. The chair they placed outside the hotel is broken; I sat on it, and it broke on me. The staff and receptionist didn't even notice. When I told them the chair broke, they came and just put it back as it was before. I got some bruises, and they didn't even say sorry.","Images":["www.google.com/local/imagery/report/?cb_client=maps_sv.tactile&image_key=!1e10!2sAF1QipNsvAfIgy0-YEGlMAIYCLHXfohxuZrYzuyLvt7v&fid=0x0:0x1f5edf542c88a65b"],"When":"2023-10-18"},{"Name":"Trina Taylor","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocJc45quf8GKvNZR2kFNJotUX3LAUzZcwSnSi3Vd4XwsjfE2M_0=s120-c-rp-mo-br100","Rating":5,"Description":"The room was clean, the staff was very friendly and helpful. We stayed here for four days, and their breakfast changed everyday which is what we really enjoyed trying new food everyday. The location  was really good. There are a lot of street food around this area.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Jason N","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0Qdx0CtChWdL4amzhVtedU6JgNzs3A9KzPS8K998c7-u-mDeTb-7WQwuTD-PPX6BcVA5wg=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"I didn't have high hopes for this hotel, but the photos and rating seemed good.  I should have been more cautious and read the reviews more carefully.  First, there is no elevator.  My fault for not checking that, so no negative rating for this.  The hotel has 8 floors so you may have to climb 8 stories to your room. The biggest shock factor was how old and beat up the rooms were.  The website pictures look nice but are either photoshopped or so old that they no longer are accurate.  The walls are dirty and covered in the blood of many dead mosquitoes.  The bathrooms used to have white grout, but now are black with mildew.  -2 rating for horribly accurate pictures.  Second, the hotel does nothing for mosquito control.  I stayed in multiple hotels throughout Myanmar and every hotel was proactive at controlling the mosquitoes.  This place does nothing and the rooms were filled with them.  We got bit multiple times during the night.  -1 rating for mosquito control.  We got the entire floor (two rooms), and one of the rooms smelled of cigarette smoke.  -1 rating for that.  +1 rating as the staff seemed nice, the breakfast was decent, and location was good.  That adds up to a +2 rating.  I would not recommend this place at all.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Sarah R","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QeFH6dzZjd_ZFLhXHZKibEzXEy8hWzFB4Qa7PutLe3CnO2G7yVfjd4VSabiCQwQYo5W-g=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"Coming from Siem Reap it took my brain a little bit to adjust to a new economy! The first hotel I booked at $20 per night was an absolute dive. I got out of there as quickly as I could! Walked into Hotel Bond having checked it out online, yes it was a higher price, but worth every penny. The staff were so welcoming when I turned up at 8 in the morning, got me settled into a room and even invited me to have breakfast. The staff carried my suitcase up the stairs and even with the shared bathroom, i never saw the other guest sharing the bathroom so there was no conflict there. The bathroom was excellent with a rainforest shower and a smaller shower head. My suggestions here would be to get some bigger shampoo and shower gel bottles, the tiny individual ones are a waste of plastic and in this case space given that it is a shared bathroom. Putting some floor mats for the bathroom would also be a good idea, 2-3 so each room can have their own.||The room was small but very comfortable and clean.||The breakfast was decent and the daily noodle dish was always vegetable only which is just perfect!||My only other recommendation would be large water refills. Whilst having large water bottles as well as small is a big step above most hotels, I would prefer to use no plastic at all. When I asked the guy at the desk where I might refill my bottle, he said he didn't know and to maybe try a pagoda, when I walked out the door it was less than 30 seconds before I saw that there are water tanks on the street all over the place and these are for anyone to use! Hurrah! Still it would be great if the hotel included water refills in their breakfast room.","Images":null,"When":""}]

title: Royal Tian Li

user_reviews:
[{"Name":"Moe Myint Mg Mg","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjWVVFX1-cyhnesb7-q-Qp_1TMMvmYE6-EKxxf6J-sEG5KvvzD1b=s120-c-rp-mo-br100","Rating":1,"Description":"I recently stayed at Royal Tian Li, and my experience was extremely disappointing from start to finish.

1. Poor Communication and Lack of Knowledge:
When I called the hotel‚Äôs operator staff to inquire about a promotion I saw on their Facebook page, they were completely clueless. They acted like they weren‚Äôt even part of the hotel staff and had no knowledge of the promotion or anything related to the hotel. It was incredibly frustrating and unprofessional.

2. Unwelcoming Reception:
Upon checking in, I found the receptionists to be just as unhelpful and lazy as the operator staff. They were unwelcoming and didn‚Äôt provide any information about the hotel, such as breakfast timings or amenities. It felt like they couldn‚Äôt care less about their guests.

3. Horrible Room Conditions:
The room was absolutely appalling. It smelled awful, and the duvet cover was full of stains. It was clear that cleanliness and guest comfort are not priorities at this hotel.

4. Embarrassing Incident at the Pool:
While my girlfriend and I were at the pool, a waiter invited us to enjoy a free BBQ. However, when I asked about the timings, a senior cashier rudely informed us that it was a staff party. This was an incredibly embarrassing and awkward moment. It‚Äôs shocking that the staff doesn‚Äôt even know their own guests and fail to communicate properly among themselves.

5. Pathetic Breakfast:
The breakfast was a joke. There was only fried rice and bread available, yet they have the audacity to call it a ‚Äúluxury hotel‚Äôs buffet.‚Äù It was far from it. They should just call it √† la carte and be done with it.

Overall, my stay at Royal Tian Li was a nightmare. The staff is unprofessional and untrained, the rooms are dirty, and the amenities are far below any acceptable standard. I would not recommend this hotel to anyone.","Images":null,"When":""},{"Name":"Kelly C","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/local-reviews/AJMZ0QdCjMUwIiBikRhCLHgN_0vyGAo1GvT8DEukiKQb1ujC_eFsFjYrQ0OvLoSxPtqmCdgvFA=s120-c-br100","Rating":0,"Description":"This hotel is perfect for a staycation.
